# Catalyst One — Single Source of Truth for Business Metrics

**Status:** PERMANENT ENGINEERING STANDARD · FOUNDATION  
**Effective:** Immediately  
**This is not a feature.** It is a foundational architectural principle for all current and future Catalyst One development.

---

## Primary Principle

**Every enterprise metric must have exactly one implementation within Catalyst One.**

All screens, dashboards, reports, APIs, Mission Control, CHANAKYA, SARATHI, and all future AI modules **must consume the same shared business calculation**.

Business logic must **never** be duplicated across modules.

If a business rule or calculation changes, it must be updated **only once** in the shared implementation — and every dependent module must automatically reflect the change.

**Single Source of Truth (SSOT) for business metrics is mandatory across the entire platform.**

---

## Applies To

Every surface that displays, computes, or narrates a metric, including:

- Screens and workspaces
- Dashboards and Mission Control
- Reports and exports
- APIs and services
- CHANAKYA (Radar, Briefing, Guide, and related intelligence)
- SARATHI and partner / channel intelligence
- All current and future AI modules and insights

---

## Covered Metrics

This principle applies to all current and future business metrics, including but not limited to:

- Operational Health Score
- Financial Health Score
- Opportunity Score
- Customer Score
- Partner Score
- Risk Scores
- KPIs
- Ratios
- Trends
- Forecasts
- Executive Metrics
- AI Insights
- Radar Direction / Operational Vector / quadrant counts
- Any future enterprise metric introduced into Catalyst One

---

## Single Implementation Rule

For each named metric:

1. **Exactly one** derive / engine / formula module owns the calculation
2. Every consumer **imports and calls** that module — never copies the formula
3. UI, APIs, Mission Control, CHANAKYA, SARATHI, and AI paths **must not** re-implement the formula inline
4. Parallel or “compatible” copies of the same formula are **forbidden**
5. The same metric name on two surfaces **must** call the same function with the same inputs

Prefer shared paths such as:

- `src/lib/**/derive-*.ts`
- `src/lib/**/*-engine*.ts`
- Domain constants that feed a single calculator

Never embed divergent formula bodies in React components, route handlers, prompt builders, or AI helpers.

---

## Change-Once Guarantee

When a business rule or formula changes:

1. Update **only** the canonical shared implementation
2. Do not patch individual screens or modules to “catch up”
3. All dependents must pick up the change through the shared import
4. If a consumer still has a local copy, **delete it** and wire to SSOT before shipping

---

## Forbidden Patterns

- Recalculating the same score in a dashboard **and** again in a table, tooltip, export, or AI summary
- Slightly different thresholds or weightings for the “same” metric across modules
- Hardcoded percentages / magic numbers that diverge from the shared engine
- AI or briefing text inventing a metric value instead of calling the shared calculator
- Mission Control, CHANAKYA, or SARATHI maintaining a private formula for a platform metric
- API responses recomputing a metric already owned by a lib module, unless the API **is** that module’s sole entry point

---

## When Adding or Changing a Metric

1. Search for existing implementations (name, aliases, related scores)
2. If one exists — **extend or fix that implementation**; do not create a second
3. If none exists — create **one** shared module, document the formula, then wire all consumers
4. If consumers currently diverge — **consolidate** before shipping
5. Document the canonical path in module rules so ownership is obvious

---

## Consistency Guarantee

Given the same enterprise data inputs, the same metric **must** always produce the same result — regardless of which screen, dashboard, report, API, Mission Control view, CHANAKYA surface, SARATHI module, or AI insight requested it.

Any discrepancy between surfaces is a **defect**.

---

## Relationship to other standards

- Strengthens `data-integrity-analytics-standard.mdc` (accuracy, explainability, real-time refresh)
- Aligns with `catalyst-one-development-charter.mdc` (do not duplicate business logic)
- Complements module engines (e.g. `chanakya-radar.mdc`)

When delivery speed conflicts with single implementation, **consolidate first** — never ship a second formula to move faster.

---

## Definition of Done (metric / analytics change)

Before marking complete:

- [ ] Canonical calculator identified or created (exactly one)
- [ ] All new/changed consumers call that calculator
- [ ] No duplicated formula left in UI, API, Mission Control, CHANAKYA, SARATHI, or AI paths touched by the change
- [ ] Formula documented at the canonical site
- [ ] Same inputs → same outputs across consumers when multiple exist

If a second implementation remains, the work is **not** production-ready.
